pt. Regulations for the Army of the Confederate States|url=https://archive.org/details/regulati00conf|place= Richmond|publisher=J.W. Randolph|date=1863}}\n* {{cite book|last=Robson|first= John S.|title=How A One-Legged Rebel Lives: Reminiscences of the Civil War; The Story of the Campaigns of Stonewall Jackson|publisher= Kessinger Publishing|date=2007|isbn=978-1-84685-665-5}}\n* {{citation|author=U.S. War Department|url=http://ehistory.osu.edu/osu/sources/records/list.cfm|title=The War of the Rebellion: a Compilation of the Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies|place=U.S. Government Printing Office|date=1880\u20131901}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Confederate States Army}}\n{{Wikiquote|Confederate States of America}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130625144353/http://www.civilwarsoldier.com/cws_confederate_soldiers.htm Confederate soldiers]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://jdc.jefferson.edu/milsurgcsa/ A Manual of Military Surgery (1863). The manual used by doctors in the CSA.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://battleofolustee.org/uniforms/uniforms.html U.S. Civil War Era Uniforms and Accouterments]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://library.duke.edu/digital collections/strong/Duke University Libraries Digital Collections \u2013 William Emerson Strong Photograph Album] 200 cartes-de-visite depicting officers in the Confederate army and navy, officials in the Confederate government, famous Confederate wives, and other notable figures of the Confederacy. Also included are 64 photographs attributed to Mathew Brady.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.confederateuniforms.org Confederate and State Regulations] at confederateuniforms.org\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.1stconfederatebattalion.org 1st Confederate Battalion, Forney's Regiment] (Living History Organization)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303102250/http://www.histclo.com/essay/war/cwa/sold/cwas-black.html Black soldiers in the U.S. Civil War]\n* [http://vault.georgiaarchives.org/cdm/landingpage/collection/confed Confederate Enlistment Oaths and Discharges of the Army of the State of Georgia]\n\n{{Field armies of the Confederate States}}\n{{American Civil War|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1861 establishments in the Confederate States of America]]\n[[Category:1865 disestablishments in the Confederate States of America]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Army| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Disbanded armies]]\n[[Category:Military history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAfrican Americans and the Confederate Army:clean up, removed: |publisher=The New York Times Company", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confederate_States_Army"}
{"title_page": "Glen Oak Country Club", "text_new": "{{notability|date=May 2013}}, \n\n'''Glen Oak Country Club''' is a country club and private [[golf course]] in [[Glen Ellyn, Illinois]] that was designed by [[Tom Bendelow]] and established in 1911.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glenoakcountryclub.org |title=Glen Oak Country Club |work= Glen Oak Country Club |accessdate=2018-07-23}}</ref> \n\nOn January 7,1909, the Pickwick Country Club was created. It had a 9 hole golf course- eventually expanded to 18 holes. Within a year, the club went bankrupt. In 1911, the property was purchased and reopened as the current Glen Oak Country Club.<ref>http://www.greatthirdrail.org/stations/main/glenoak.html</ref>\n\nIn the past bordering the club to the north- which is the Prairie Path today, was an interurban train stop. Many members lived in Chicago and would take the train out of the city to this club. Upon exit, a carriage would take the members along Hill Ave to the club house.<ref>Document on wall of Glen Oak CC</ref>\n\nAlong with the golf course, it also has a swimming pool, and facility for trap shooting for member use on the club's south border. On the ninth hole, there is a Halfway House to refresh the players with drinks, beverages, and food. As the weather transitions from fall to winter many members change from golfing to The Skeet and Trap Club, which features a new remodeled Lodge area.\n\nOver the years, the club has been expanded and remodeled to the club it is today.\n\nSome of the famous people that have visited the club are famous athletes like MLB Players [[Jorge Soler]], [[Carlos Zambrano]], [[Michael Jordan]](basketball), [[Bobby Rahal]] (retired race car driver), [[Arnold Palmer]](golfer), and PGA Golfer [[Mark Wilson (golfer)|Mark Wilson]].\n\n==Golf==\n\nThe club mascot is Pinki - a former caddy of which there is a statue of in front of the club and a tournament named after him. The 18 hole course plays 6,503 yards and [[par (golf scoring format)|par]] 72 with a 72.1 rating. The course features relatively small greens protected by [[bunkers]] with [[fairways]]; it is especially notable for the extensive treeline on most holes. {{As of|2018}}, Danny Mulhearn is the head [[golf professional]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pga.com/professionals/danny-e-mulhearn-pga |title=Danny E. Mulhearn, PGA |work=[[Professional Golfers' Association of America]] |accessdate=2018-07-23}}</ref> \n\nThe club hosted the [[1943 Women's Western Open]], won by [[LPGA|Ladies Professional Golf Association (LPGA)]] co-founder [[Patty Berg]], one of her still-record 11 [[Women's major golf championships|LPGA Tour major championship wins]]. The club hosted the [[Professional Golfers' Association of America]]\u2019s (PGA) 1915 [[Western Open]], won by [[Tom McNamara (golfer)|Tom McNamara]]. The course hosted the [[Illinois PGA]]\u2019s 1962 [[Illinois Open Championship]], won by John Paul Jones.\n\nThe club participates with a caddy program where the traditional caddy carries the golf bag for the members. Golf carts are available should the member not want to walk the course. The club also participates in the Evans Caddie College Scholarship.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.golfadvisor.com/courses/5224-glen-oak-country-club/ {{coord|41.8778|-88.0431|type:landmark|display=title}}][[Geographic coordinate system|Coordinates]]: <span class=\"plainlinks nourlexpansion\">[//tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?pagename=Glen_Oak_Country_Club&params=41.8778_N_88.0431_W_type:landmark <span class=\"geo-nondefault\"><span class=\"geo-dms\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\"><span class=\"latitude\">41\u00b052\u203240\u2033N</span> <span class=\"longitude\">88\u00b002\u203235\u2033W</span></span></span><span class=\"geo-multi-punct\"> / </span><span class=\"geo-default\"><span class=\"geo-dec\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\">41.8778\u00b0N 88.0431\u00b0W</span><span style=\"display:none\"> / <span class=\"geo\">41.8778; -88.0431</span></span></span>]</span>\n\n[[Category:Coordinates on Wikidata]]\n[[Category:Golf clubs and courses in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in DuPage County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Glen Ellyn, Illinois]]\n[[Category:1911 establishments in Illinois]]\n\n\n{{golfcourse-stub}}\n{{Illinois-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{notability|date=May 2013}}, \n\n'''Glen Oak Country Club''' is a country club and private [[golf course]] in [[Glen Ellyn, Illinois]] that was designed by [[Tom Bendelow]] and established in 1911.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glenoakcountryclub.org |title=Glen Oak Country Club |work= Glen Oak Country Club |accessdate=2018-07-23}}</ref> \n\nOn January 7,1909, the Pickwick Country Club was created. It had a 9 hole golf course- eventually expanded to 18 holes. Within a year, the club went bankrupt. In 1911, the property was purchased and reopened as the current Glen Oak Country Club.<ref>http://www.greatthirdrail.org/stations/main/glenoak.html</ref>\n\nIn the past bordering the club to the north- which is the Prairie Path today, was an interurban train stop. Many members lived in Chicago and would take the train out of the city to this club. Upon exit, a carriage would take the members along Hill Ave to the club house.<ref>Document on wall of Glen Oak CC</ref>\n\nAlong with the golf course, it also has a swimming pool, and facility for trap shooting for member use on the club's south border. On the ninth hole, there is a Halfway House to refresh the players with drinks, beverages, and food. As the weather transitions from fall to winter many members change from golfing to The Skeet and Trap Club, which features a new remodeled Lodge area.\n\nOver the years, the club has been expanded and remodeled to the club it is today.\n\nSome of the famous people that have visited the club are famous athletes like MLB Players [[Jorge Soler]], [[Carlos Zambrano]], [[Michael Jordon]](basketball), [[Bobby Rahal]] (retired race car driver), [[Arnold Palmer]](golfer), and PGA Golfer [[Mark Wilson (golfer)|Mark Wilson]].\n\n==Golf==\n\nThe club mascot is Pinki - a former caddy of which there is a statue of in front of the club and a tournament named after him. The 18 hole course plays 6,503 yards and [[par (golf scoring format)|par]] 72 with a 72.1 rating. The course features relatively small greens protected by [[bunkers]] with [[fairways]]; it is especially notable for the extensive treeline on most holes. {{As of|2018}}, Danny Mulhearn is the head [[golf professional]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pga.com/professionals/danny-e-mulhearn-pga |title=Danny E. Mulhearn, PGA |work=[[Professional Golfers' Association of America]] |accessdate=2018-07-23}}</ref> \n\nThe club hosted the [[1943 Women's Western Open]], won by [[LPGA|Ladies Professional Golf Association (LPGA)]] co-founder [[Patty Berg]], one of her still-record 11 [[Women's major golf championships|LPGA Tour major championship wins]]. The club hosted the [[Professional Golfers' Association of America]]\u2019s (PGA) 1915 [[Western Open]], won by [[Tom McNamara (golfer)|Tom McNamara]]. The course hosted the [[Illinois PGA]]\u2019s 1962 [[Illinois Open Championship]], won by John Paul Jones.\n\nThe club participates with a caddy program where the traditional caddy carries the golf bag for the members. Golf carts are available should the member not want to walk the course. The club also participates in the Evans Caddie College Scholarship.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.golfadvisor.com/courses/5224-glen-oak-country-club/ {{coord|41.8778|-88.0431|type:landmark|display=title}}][[Geographic coordinate system|Coordinates]]: <span class=\"plainlinks nourlexpansion\">[//tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?pagename=Glen_Oak_Country_Club&params=41.8778_N_88.0431_W_type:landmark <span class=\"geo-nondefault\"><span class=\"geo-dms\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\"><span class=\"latitude\">41\u00b052\u203240\u2033N</span> <span class=\"longitude\">88\u00b002\u203235\u2033W</span></span></span><span class=\"geo-multi-punct\"> / </span><span class=\"geo-default\"><span class=\"geo-dec\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\">41.8778\u00b0N 88.0431\u00b0W</span><span style=\"display:none\"> / <span class=\"geo\">41.8778; -88.0431</span></span></span>]</span>\n\n[[Category:Coordinates on Wikidata]]\n[[Category:Golf clubs and courses in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in DuPage County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Glen Ellyn, Illinois]]\n[[Category:1911 establishments in Illinois]]\n\n\n{{golfcourse-stub}}\n{{Illinois-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glen_Oak_Country_Club"}
{"title_page": "Bertoleoni family", "text_new": "[[File:Bertoleoni photo.jpg|thumb|right|300px|King Carlo I Bertoleoni and his family, which the Bertoleoni family claims was displayed in Buckingham Palace with the caption \"The royal family of Tavolara, in the gulf of Terranova, the smallest kingdom in the world.\"<ref>{{cite journal |year=1962 |month= |title= Semana |journal=Semana |volume=60 |issue=1154\u20131166 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=14UcAQAAMAAJ }}</ref>]]\n\n'''Bertoleoni''' is the self-proclaimed ruling family of the self-styled \"[[Kingdom of Tavolara]]\" ([[Sardinia]], Italy), which claimed to be \"the smallest kingdom of the world\" (now extinguished). The members of this family were also the only inhabitants of this island (whose land is owned partly by the Marzano family in Rome, and partly by a [[NATO]] military base) that had been abandoned in the 1730s because of [[Barbary pirates|North-African piracy]] in the area. They sustained themselves by goat farming and fishing. Currently, the mock-kingdom is a tourist attraction for the 50 or so native inhabitants of the island, where the current \"king\" and \"crown princess\" run its two restaurants and sell souvenirs to visitors of the Natural Park.\n\nA Giuseppe Bertoleoni claimed that during a hunting trip, [[Charles Albert of Sardinia|Charles Albert]], King of [[Sardinia]], verbally appointed him \"king of Tavolara\" in 1836. According to Giuseppe Bertoleoni, Charles Albert also (verbally) sanctioned the use of the title \"Prince\" for the oldest male heir, and the titles \"Lord of the Islands\" (Signore delle Isole) and \"Lady of the Sea\" (Signora del Mare) for the younger children of the king.\n\nThe present [[pretender]] to the throne is \"King\" Tonino, an Italian citizen who runs ''Da Tonino'', a restaurant on the island.\n\n==Giuseppe (1836\u20131845)==\nBorn December 20, 1778, on the nearby island of [[La Maddalena]], Giuseppe Celestino Bertoleoni Poli was a shepherd and the only inhabitant of the island before Charles Albert, the King of Sardinia's visit. He claimed to have impressed him as an educated man and to have been made king of the island shortly thereafter. He brought his two families from other islands to live with him. The Italian government tried to prosecute him for [[bigamy]], but failed because of his title.<ref>{{cite book |title=Itin\u00e9raire de l'ile de Sardaigne pour faire suite au Voyage en cette contr\u00e9e |publisher=Bocca |last=Ferrero della Marmora |first=Alberto |authorlink= |year=1860 |location=Turin |pages=[https://archive.org/details/itinrairedelile01dellgoog/page/n197 190]\u2013193 |url=https://archive.org/details/itinrairedelile01dellgoog }}</ref><ref>[[David Wallechinsky|Wallechinsky, David]], and [[Amy Wallace]] (2005), ''The New Book of Lists'', pp 383-384, {{ISBN|1-84195-719-4}}</ref>\nPassed kingdom to son Paolo in 1845; died 1849.<ref>{{cite book |title=Voyages en Corse, \u00e0 l'ile d'Elbe et en Sardaigne |last=Valery |first=Antoine-Claude Pasquin |authorlink= |year=1837 |location=Paris |volume=2 |page=9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iC4MAAAAYAAJ }}</ref><ref>\"The Island of Sardinia\", ''Blackwoods Edinburgh Magazine'', July 1849, p 43</ref><ref>Vuillier, Gaston (1896), ''The Forgotten Isles: Impressions of Travel in the Balearic Isles, Corsica and Sardinia'', trans. Frederic Breton, p 386</ref> Giuseppe's origins are a mystery. Because he claimed to be more highly educated than the average Sardinian shepherd, some have speculated on no ground that he was a fugitive member of the [[Carbonari]], an exiled French aristocrat, or even the [[Lost Dauphin]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Unknown Europe |last=Meissner |first=Hans Otto |authorlink=Hans-Otto Meissner |others=trans. Florence and Isabel McHugh |year=1963 |publisher=Blackie & Sons |location=London and Glasgow |pages=15\u201316 |url= }}</ref>\n\n==Paolo I (1845\u20131886)==\n[[Image:Tavolara King's grave.JPG|thumb|right|Royal tomb of Paolo I and Pasqua Favale]]\n\nSon of Giuseppe Bertoleoni and Laura Ornano, born 1815. In 1839 he visited King [[Charles Albert]] in [[Turin]] and obtained a royal charter to Tavolara. During this period, the Italian patriot [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] was associated with the Bertoleoni family, often visiting Paolo's relatives on the islands of [[La Maddalena]] and [[Caprera]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Le relazioni diplomatiche fra la Gran Bretagna e il Regno di Sardegna |series=ser. 3, vol. 2 |last=Curato |first=Federico, ed. |year=1961 |publisher=Istituto Storico Italiano per l'Eta Moderna e Contemporanea |location=Rome |page=287 |quote=Egli, il Garibaldi, passa il suo tempo alla pesca e alla caccia, la notte va di frequente a visitare la Famiglia Bertoleoni, ed il giorno, che resta a casa, se la fa leggendo.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Garibaldi at Caprera |last=Vecchi |first=Candido Augusto |year=1862 |publisher=Macmillan and Company |location=Cambridge |pages=95\u2013108 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xxVIAQAAMAAJ }}</ref>\n\nAfter the creation of the [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian Kingdom]] in 1861, Paolo pressed and obtained recognition for Tavolara from [[Victor Emmanuel II]] {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}. After he fell ill in 1882, his wife Pasqua Favale acted as regent until his death on May 30, 1886.<ref>\"E morto il Re!\" ''La Sardegna'', June 8, 1886, p 1</ref><ref>Saragat, Giovanni, \"Paolo I Re di Tavolara. Un principe per burla. Storia e aneddoti.\" ''Il Nuovo Giornale'', Oct 16-17, 1895</ref>  A number of newspapers published the report that on his deathbed he asked that the kingdom die with him, and that his family therefore established a republic. These reports, however, were erroneous.<ref>{{cite book |title=Unknown Europe |last=Meissner |first=Hans Otto |authorlink=Hans-Otto Meissner |others=trans. Florence and Isabel McHugh |year=1963 |publisher=Blackie & Sons |location=London and Glasgow |page=23 |url= }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Bertoleoni sketch.jpg|thumb|left|300px|King Carlo I, royal consort Maddalena Favale, and three Ladies of the Sea (Hale, 1904).]]\n\n==Carlo I (1886\u20131927)==\nSon of Paolo I and Pasqua Favale, born 1845. In the summer of 1900 the British naval vessel [[HMS Vulcan (1889)|HMS ''Vulcan'']] visited Tavolara, and the officers took a photograph of King Carlo and his family to hang in [[Queen Victoria]]'s collection of royal portraits in [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref>{{cite journal |year=1962 |month= |title= Semana|journal=Semana |volume=60 |issue=1154\u20131166 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=14UcAQAAMAAJ }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |year=1976 |month= |title=Forgotten Flags: Tavolara |journal=The Flag Bulletin |publisher=Flag Research Center |location=Winchester, Mass |volume=15-17 |issue= |page=131 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mCIrAQAAIAAJ }}</ref> By 1904, however, Carlo was king in name only, having no ambition to rule. He is reported to have said, \"I do not care to be a king. It is enough for me to make as fine lobster-pots as did my father.\" He was persuaded to reign, however, until his death, which was reported either Nov 6, 1927, at [[Olbia]], or Jan 31, 1928, at [[Ventimiglia]] on the Italian Riviera.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hale |first=Walter |date=Nov 1904 |title=The Search for a Lost Republic |journal=Harper's Monthly Magazine |volume=CIX |issue=DCXLIX |pages=929\u2013936 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=flsCAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA929 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tavolara's King Dies; Ruled Tiniest Realm; Charles Bartoleoni Was Monarch of Small Island Off Sardinia's Coast |work=New York Times |page=27 |date=February 1, 1928 |accessdate=14 April 2009 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/02/01/archives/tavolaras-king-dies-ruled-tiniest-realm-charles-bartoleoni-was.html }}</ref>\n\n==Mariangela (1927\u20131929)==\nDaughter of Paolo I and Pasqua Favale, born 1841, she took up the crown at the request of her nephew Paolo (Carlo's son and designated successor) during his absence from the island (he had left the island looking for a job). When Mariangela died April 6, 1934, it was reported that Italy would inherit the kingdom.<ref>\"Princess Dies at Age of 100 on Lonely Island,\" ''Chicago Daily Tribune'', July 1, 1934, p F2</ref><ref>\"Italy Gets Queen's Island of Tavolara,\" ''Hartford Courant'', July 9, 1934, p 15</ref>\n\n==Paolo II (1929\u20131962)==\nSon of Carlo I and Maddalena Favale, born 1897. Married 1930 to Italia Murru and initiated a renaissance of the monarchy. Appointed his cousin Prince Ernesto Carlo Geremia as Lieutenant General of the Kingdom. After Paolo's death Dec 2, 1962, the widowed Queen Italia Murru retired to [[Porto San Paolo]] on Sardinia, wintering at [[Capo Testa]], until her death in 2003 at age 95. Paolo II was the last to actively rule Tavolara (numbering then about 50 inhabitants). At the end of his reign, half the island was occupied by a NATO military installation.<ref>{{cite news |title=E' morto ieri il \"re\" dell'isola di Tavolara |work=La Stampa |date=Dec 3, 1962 |page=11 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0011/articleid,0089_02_1962_0273_0011_17677686 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Carlo II (1962\u20131993)==\nEldest son of Paolo II and Italia Murru, born 1931. Married, no issue. Died May 1993 at [[Capo Testa]], Sardinia.<ref>{{cite news |title=E' morto il \"re pescatore\" |first=Corrado |last=Grandesso |work=La Stampa |date=May 9, 1993 |page=13 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0013/articleid,0786_01_1993_0126_0013_11130126 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref> During the 1960s and 70s, his cousins Maria Molinas Bertoleoni (1869\u20131974) and Laura Molinas Bertoleoni (d. 1979), both daughters of Mariangela and Bachisio Molinas, also laid claim to the vacant \"throne\".<ref>\"Oldest Claimant to Royalty is 100,\" Associated Press, July 5, 1969</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=La principessa di Tavolare ha compiuto ieri 104 anni  |work=La Stampa |date=July 3, 1973 |page=9 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0009/articleid,1507_02_1973_0153_0009_21217883 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Morta la principessa dell'isola di Tavolara ha compiuto ieri 104 anni  |work=La Stampa |date=Feb 12, 1974 |page=8 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0008/articleid,1111_01_1974_0034A_0008_21400111 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Morta ultracentenaria l'ultima principessa del regno di Tavolara |work=La Stampa |date=Feb 28, 1979 |page=11 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0011/articleid,1070_01_1979_0048_0012_15312528 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Tonino (1993\u2013 )==\nAntonio (Tonino) Bertoleoni, second son of Paolo II and Italia Murru, was born in 1933. He is the owner of ''Da Tonino'' restaurant; his sister Princess Maddalena owns ''La Corona'' restaurant nearby. Following the return of [[Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples|Vittorio Emanuele of Naples]] to his native Italy in 2002, Tonino vowed an appeal to him, as heir to the [[House of Savoy]], for recognition of the Tavolaran kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gigi |last=Padovani |title=Cartoline d'estate: La favola del re barcaiolo |work=La Stampa |date=Aug 3, 2005 |page=16 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0016/articleid,0236_01_2005_0211_0016_1819551/anews,true |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref> Tonino's children by Maria \"Pompea\" Romano (1932\u20132010) are Loredana, Paola, and Giuseppe.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alessandro |last=Pirina |title=\u00c8 morta Pompea, moglie dell'ultimo re di Tavolara |work=La Nuova Sardegna |date=March 13, 2010 |url=http://ricerca.gelocal.it/lanuovasardegna/archivio/lanuovasardegna/2010/03/13/SL4PO_SL403.html |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Ido |last=Liven |title=The island realm of an 'ordinary' king |url=https://www.thestar.com/Travel/article/432471 |work=Toronto Star |date=May 31, 2008 |accessdate=12 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* AA.VV., ''Una montagna in mezzo al mare'', ed. Taphros 2005.\n* Della Marmora, Alberto. ''Viaggio in Sardegna'', Forni, Bologna 1985.\n* Finelli, Riccardo. ''C'\u00e8 di mezzo il mare - Viaggio nelle micro-isole italiane'', Incontri ed., Sassuolo 2008.\n* Fioretti, Ovidio. [http://www.ceramichesarde.it/pagine/rubriche/tavolara.htm \"La corona senza reame,\"] ''Almanacco di Cagliari 1989''.\n* {{cite news |title=Tavolara e il suo Re |first=Alberto |last=Fumi |work=La Stampa |date=Aug 22, 1991 |page=14 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0014/articleid,1294_02_1991_0185_0014_19145339 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}\n* Geremia, Ernesto Carlo, and Gino Ragnetti (2005), ''Tavolara - l'Isola dei Re'', Mursia, Milano. {{ISBN|88-425-3441-2}}.\n* Graziani, Graziano. ''Stati d'eccezione'', ed. dell'Asino, Roma 2012.\n* Hale, Walter (Nov 1904). \"The Search for a Lost Republic\". ''Harper's Monthly Magazine''. CIX (DCXLIX): 929\u2013936.\n* Manca, Tania. ''Viaggiatori europei. Dall'esplorazione del mondo al viaggio in Sardegna (700 e 800), Carlo Delfino, Sassari 2005.\n* Mazzucchelli, Mario. ''Gioacchino Murat'', Dall'Oglio, Milano 1962.\n* Murineddu (a cura di), Antonio. ''Gallura'', Fossataro, Cagliari 1962.\n* Papurello, Alfredina. ''Tavolara Signora del Mare'', Carlo Delfino, Sassari 2012.\n* Sotgiu, Giovanna. ''Arcipelago di La Maddalena - 1839-1843 - La Divisione delle terre - Giuseppe Bertoleoni Re di Tavolara'', Lo Scoglio, La Maddalena 2002.\n* Tribuna Araldica, ''Famiglie di Genova, estinte e viventi, nobili e popolari'', ed.Europea di Araldica, parte 1, Genova 1983.\n* Valery, Antoine Claude. ''Viaggio in Sardegna'', Ilisso, Nuoro 1999.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=02MB4czg_DI \"Isola di Tavolara - La Famiglia Bertoleoni 25/09/1958\"] - 1958 newsreel on YouTube\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P2BHNX9llJ0 \"Incontro con il Re di Tavolara\"] - 2009 interview with Antonio Bertoleoni on YouTube\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bertoleoni}}\n[[Category:People from Sardinia]]\n[[Category:History of Sardinia]]\n[[Category:Italian royal houses]]\n[[Category:Lists of monarchs]]\n[[Category:Micronational leaders]]\n[[Category:19th-century monarchs in Europe]]\n[[Category:Heads of state of former countries]]\n[[Category:Heads of state of unrecognized or largely unrecognized states]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Bertoleoni photo.jpg|thumb|right|300px|King Carlo I Bertoleoni and his family, which the Bertoleoni family claims was displayed in Buckingham Palace with the caption \"The royal family of Tavolara, in the gulf of Terranova, the smallest kingdom in the world.\"<ref>{{cite journal |year=1962 |month= |title= Semana |journal=Semana |volume=60 |issue=1154\u20131166 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=14UcAQAAMAAJ }}</ref>]]\n\n'''Bertoleoni''' is the self-proclaimed ruling family of the self-styled \"[[Kingdom of Tavolara]]\" ([[Sardinia]], Italy), which claimed to be \"the smallest kingdom of the world\" (now extinguished). The members of this family were also the only inhabitants of this island (whose land is owned partly by the Marzano family in Rome, and partly by a [[NATO]] military base) that had been abandoned in the 1730s because of [[Barbary pirates|North-African piracy]] in the area. They sustained themselves by goat farming and fishing. Currently, the mock-kingdom is a tourist attraction for the 50 or so native inhabitants of the island, where the current \"king\" and \"crown princess\" run its two restaurants and sell souvenirs to visitors of the Natural Park.\n\nA Giuseppe Bertoleoni claimed that during a hunting trip, [[Charles Albert of Sardinia|Charles Albert]], King of [[Sardinia]], verbally appointed him \"king of Tavolara\" in 1836. According to Giuseppe Bertoleoni, Charles Albert also (verbally) sanctioned the use of the title \"Prince\" for the oldest male heir, and the titles \"Lord of the Islands\" (Signore delle Isole) and \"Lady of the Sea\" (Signora del Mare) for the younger children of the king.\n\nThe present [[pretender]] to the throne is \"King\" Tonino, an Italian citizen who runs ''Da Tonino'', a restaurant on the island.\n\n==Giuseppe (1836\u20131845)==\nBorn December 20, 1778, on the nearby island of [[La Maddalena]], Giuseppe Celestino Bertoleoni Poli was a shepherd and the only inhabitant of the island before Charles Albert, the King of Sardinia's visit. He claimed to have impressed him as an educated man and to have been made king of the island shortly thereafter. He brought his two families from other islands to live with him. The Italian government tried to prosecute him for [[bigamy]], but failed because of his title.<ref>{{cite book |title=Itin\u00e9raire de l'ile de Sardaigne pour faire suite au Voyage en cette contr\u00e9e |publisher=Bocca |last=Ferrero della Marmora |first=Alberto |authorlink= |year=1860 |location=Turin |pages=[https://archive.org/details/itinrairedelile01dellgoog/page/n197 190]\u2013193 |url=https://archive.org/details/itinrairedelile01dellgoog }}</ref><ref>[[David Wallechinsky|Wallechinsky, David]], and [[Amy Wallace]] (2005), ''The New Book of Lists'', pp 383-384, {{ISBN|1-84195-719-4}}</ref>\nPassed kingdom to son Paolo in 1845; died 1849.<ref>{{cite book |title=Voyages en Corse, \u00e0 l'ile d'Elbe et en Sardaigne |last=Valery |first=Antoine-Claude Pasquin |authorlink= |year=1837 |location=Paris |volume=2 |page=9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iC4MAAAAYAAJ }}</ref><ref>\"The Island of Sardinia\", ''Blackwoods Edinburgh Magazine'', July 1849, p 43</ref><ref>Vuillier, Gaston (1896), ''The Forgotten Isles: Impressions of Travel in the Balearic Isles, Corsica and Sardinia'', trans. Frederic Breton, p 386</ref> Giuseppe's origins are a mystery. Because he claimed to be more highly educated than the average Sardinian shepherd, some have speculated on no ground that he was a fugitive member of the [[Carbonari]], an exiled French aristocrat, or even the [[Lost Dauphin]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Unknown Europe |last=Meissner |first=Hans Otto |authorlink=Hans-Otto Meissner |others=trans. Florence and Isabel McHugh |year=1963 |publisher=Blackie & Sons |location=London and Glasgow |pages=15\u201316 |url= }}</ref>\n\n==Paolo I (1845\u20131886)==\n[[Image:Tavolara King's grave.JPG|thumb|right|Royal tomb of Paolo I and Pasqua Favale]]\n\nSon of Giuseppe Bertoleoni and Laura Ornano, born 1815. In 1839 he visited King [[Charles Albert]] in [[Turin]] and obtained a royal charter to Tavolara. During this period, the Italian patriot [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] was associated with the Bertoleoni family, often visiting Paolo's relatives on the islands of [[La Maddalena]] and [[Caprera]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Le relazioni diplomatiche fra la Gran Bretagna e il Regno di Sardegna |series=ser. 3, vol. 2 |last=Curato |first=Federico, ed. |year=1961 |publisher=Istituto Storico Italiano per l'Eta Moderna e Contemporanea |location=Rome |page=287 |quote=Egli, il Garibaldi, passa il suo tempo alla pesca e alla caccia, la notte va di frequente a visitare la Famiglia Bertoleoni, ed il giorno, che resta a casa, se la fa leggendo.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Garibaldi at Caprera |last=Vecchi |first=Candido Augusto |year=1862 |publisher=Macmillan and Company |location=Cambridge |pages=95\u2013108 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xxVIAQAAMAAJ }}</ref>\n\nAfter the creation of the [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian Kingdom]] in 1861, Paolo pressed and obtained recognition for Tavolara from [[Victor Emmanuel II]] {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}. After he fell ill in 1882, his wife Pasqua Favale acted as regent until his death on May 30, 1886.<ref>\"E morto il Re!\" ''La Sardegna'', June 8, 1886, p 1</ref><ref>Saragat, Giovanni, \"Paolo I Re di Tavolara. Un principe per burla. Storia e aneddoti.\" ''Il Nuovo Giornale'', Oct 16-17, 1895</ref>  A number of newspapers published the report that on his deathbed he asked that the kingdom die with him, and that his family therefore established a republic. These reports, however, were erroneous.<ref>{{cite book |title=Unknown Europe |last=Meissner |first=Hans Otto |authorlink=Hans-Otto Meissner |others=trans. Florence and Isabel McHugh |year=1963 |publisher=Blackie & Sons |location=London and Glasgow |page=23 |url= }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Bertoleoni sketch.jpg|thumb|left|300px|King Carlo I, royal consort Maddalena Favale, and three Ladies of the Sea (Hale, 1904).]]\n\n==Carlo I (1886\u20131927)==\nSon of Paolo I and Pasqua Favale, born 1845. In the summer of 1900 the British naval vessel [[HMS Vulcan (1889)|HMS ''Vulcan'']] visited Tavolara, and the officers took a photograph of King Carlo and his family to hang in [[Queen Victoria]]'s collection of royal portraits in [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref>{{cite journal |year=1962 |month= |title= Semana|journal=Semana |volume=60 |issue=1154\u20131166 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=14UcAQAAMAAJ }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |year=1976 |month= |title=Forgotten Flags: Tavolara |journal=The Flag Bulletin |publisher=Flag Research Center |location=Winchester, Mass |volume=15-17 |issue= |page=131 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mCIrAQAAIAAJ }}</ref> By 1904, however, Carlo was king in name only, having no ambition to rule. He is reported to have said, \"I do not care to be a king. It is enough for me to make as fine lobster-pots as did my father.\" He was persuaded to reign, however, until his death, which was reported either Nov 6, 1927, at [[Olbia]], or Jan 31, 1928, at [[Ventimiglia]] on the Italian Riviera.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hale |first=Walter |date=Nov 1904 |title=The Search for a Lost Republic |journal=Harper's Monthly Magazine |volume=CIX |issue=DCXLIX |pages=929\u2013936 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=flsCAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA929 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tavolara's King Dies; Ruled Tiniest Realm; Charles Bartoleoni Was Monarch of Small Island Off Sardinia's Coast |work=New York Times |page=27 |date=February 1, 1928 |accessdate=14 April 2009 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/02/01/archives/tavolaras-king-dies-ruled-tiniest-realm-charles-bartoleoni-was.html }}</ref>\n\n==Mariangela (1927\u20131929)==\nDaughter of Paolo I and Pasqua Favale, born 1841, she took up the crown at the request of her nephew Paolo (Carlo's son and designated successor) during his absence from the island (he had left the island looking for a job). When Mariangela died April 6, 1934, it was reported that Italy would inherit the kingdom.<ref>\"Princess Dies at Age of 100 on Lonely Island,\" ''Chicago Daily Tribune'', July 1, 1934, p F2</ref><ref>\"Italy Gets Queen's Island of Tavolara,\" ''Hartford Courant'', July 9, 1934, p 15</ref>\n\n==Paolo II (1929\u20131962)==\nSon of Carlo I and Maddalena Favale, born 1897. Married 1930 to Italia Murru and initiated a renaissance of the monarchy. Appointed his cousin Prince Ernesto Carlo Geremia as Lieutenant General of the Kingdom. After Paolo's death Dec 2, 1962, the widowed Queen Italia Murru retired to [[Porto San Paolo]] on Sardinia, wintering at [[Capo Testa]], until her death in 2003 at age 95. Paolo II was the last to actively rule Tavolara (numbering then about 50 inhabitants). At the end of his reign, half the island was occupied by a NATO military installation.<ref>{{cite news |title=E' morto ieri il \"re\" dell'isola di Tavolara |work=La Stampa |date=Dec 3, 1962 |page=11 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0011/articleid,0089_02_1962_0273_0011_17677686 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Carlo II (1962\u20131993)==\nEldest son of Paolo II and Italia Murru, born 1931. Married, no issue. Died May 1993 at [[Capo Testa]], Sardinia.<ref>{{cite news |title=E' morto il \"re pescatore\" |first=Corrado |last=Grandesso |work=La Stampa |date=May 9, 1993 |page=13 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0013/articleid,0786_01_1993_0126_0013_11130126 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref> During the 1960s and 70s, his cousins Maria Molinas Bertoleoni (1869\u20131974) and Laura Molinas Bertoleoni (d. 1979), both daughters of Mariangela and Bachisio Molinas, also laid claim to the vacant \"throne\".<ref>\"Oldest Claimant to Royalty is 100,\" Associated Press, July 5, 1969</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=La principessa di Tavolare ha compiuto ieri 104 anni  |work=La Stampa |date=July 3, 1973 |page=9 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0009/articleid,1507_02_1973_0153_0009_21217883 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Morta la principessa dell'isola di Tavolara ha compiuto ieri 104 anni  |work=La Stampa |date=Feb 12, 1974 |page=8 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0008/articleid,1111_01_1974_0034A_0008_21400111 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Morta ultracentenaria l'ultima principessa del regno di Tavolara |work=La Stampa |date=Feb 28, 1979 |page=11 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0011/articleid,1070_01_1979_0048_0012_15312528 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Tonino (1993\u2013 )==\nAntonio (Tonino) Bertoleoni, second son of Paolo II and Italia Murru, was born in 1933. He is the owner of ''Da Tonino'' restaurant; his sister Princess Maddalena owns ''La Corona'' restaurant nearby. Following the return of [[Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples|Vittorio Emanuele of Naples]] to his native Italy in 2002, Tonino vowed an appeal to him, as heir to the [[House of Savoy]], for recognition of the Tavolaran kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gigi |last=Padovani |title=Cartoline d'estate: La favola del re barcaiolo |work=La Stampa |date=Aug 3, 2005 |page=16 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0016/articleid,0236_01_2005_0211_0016_1819551/anews,true |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref> Tonino's children by Maria \"Pompea\" Romano (1932\u20132010) are Loredana, Paola, and Giuseppe.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alessandro |last=Pirina |title=\u00c8 morta Pompea, moglie dell'ultimo re di Tavolara |work=La Nuova Sardegna |date=March 13, 2010 |url=http://ricerca.gelocal.it/lanuovasardegna/archivio/lanuovasardegna/2010/03/13/SL4PO_SL403.html |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |first=Ido |last=Liven |title=The island realm of an 'ordinary' king |url=https://www.thestar.com/Travel/article/432471 |work=Toronto Star |date=May 31, 2008 |accessdate=12 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* AA.VV., ''Una montagna in mezzo al mare'', ed. Taphros 2005.\n* Della Marmora, Alberto. ''Viaggio in Sardegna'', Forni, Bologna 1985.\n* Finelli, Riccardo. ''C'\u00e8 di mezzo il mare - Viaggio nelle micro-isole italiane'', Incontri ed., Sassuolo 2008.\n* Fioretti, Ovidio. [http://www.ceramichesarde.it/pagine/rubriche/tavolara.htm \"La corona senza reame,\"] ''Almanacco di Cagliari 1989''.\n* {{cite news |title=Tavolara e il suo Re |first=Alberto |last=Fumi |work=La Stampa |date=Aug 22, 1991 |page=14 |url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0014/articleid,1294_02_1991_0185_0014_19145339 |accessdate=28 March 2012 }}\n* Geremia, Ernesto Carlo, and Gino Ragnetti (2005), ''Tavolara - l'Isola dei Re'', Mursia, Milano. {{ISBN|