gles Discography for Apex Records - 76000 series - CA|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref> both with \"Walk Away\"<ref name=Diamond/><ref name=Apex/>\n* [[Kay Kyser]] (recorded April 30, 1940, Columbia) with \"Blue Lovebird\"<ref name=Col35200/>\n* [[Guy Lombardo]] (Decca) with \"Blue Lovebird\"<ref name=Decca3000/>\n* [[Bob Manning (pop singer)|Bob Manning]] (Capitol),<ref name=Cap2000>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/Capitol2000.htm|title=Capitol 2000 - 2500, 78rpm numerical listing discography|website=78discography.com}}</ref> Australian Capitol,<ref name=CapAus>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/c/capitol-1-oz.html|title=78 Discography for Capitol Records - OZ|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref><ref name=Cap2000/><ref name=CapAus/> UK Capitol (1953)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/c/capitol-uk-13000.html|title=78 Discography for Capitol Records - UK CL 13000 series|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref>\n* [[Warne Marsh]] \u2013 ''A Ballad Album'' (1983)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Mat Mathews]] Quintet (released 1952 by Brunswick) with \"Bag's Groove\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/b/brunswick.html|title=45 Discography for Brunswick Records - US|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref>\n* [[Glenn Miller]] \u2013 1940<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Gerry Mulligan]] \u2013 ''Pleyel Jazz Concert Vol. 1'' (1954)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Willie Nelson]] on his [[American Classic]] album (2009)\n* [[Charlie Parker]] with the [[Woody Herman]] Orchestra \u2013 1951<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Joshua Redman]] and [[Brad Mehldau]] on ''[[Nearness_(album)|Nearness]]'' (2016)\n* [[Della Reese]] on ''An Evening with Della Reese'', 1958<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secondhandsongs.com/work/10851|title=Original versions of The Nearness of You written by Hoagy Carmichael, Ned Washington -  SecondHandSongs|website=www.secondhandsongs.com}}</ref>\n* [[The Roommates]] (1963, Philips) with \"Don't Cheat On Me\"<ref name=Philips/>\n* [[George Shearing]] and [[Nancy Wilson (jazz singer)|Nancy Wilson]] \u2013 ''The Swingin's Mutual'' (1960)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Dinah Shore]] (recorded June 25, 1940, Bluebird) with \"Maybe\"<ref name=Blue10500/>\n* [[Tab Smith]] ([[Checker Records|Checker]])<ref name=Checker-1>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/Checker.htm|title=Checker Records 78rpm numerical listing discography|website=78discography.com}}</ref><ref name=Checker-2>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/c/checker.html|title=45 discography for Checker Records|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref> and [[Quality Records|Quality]]<ref name=Quality>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/q/quality-ca-k-series.html|title=Singles Discography for Quality Records - CA - K series|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref> both with \"[[Because of You (1940 song)|Because of You]]\"<ref name=Checker-1/><ref name=Checker-2/><ref name=Quality/>\n* [[Reinhold Svensson]] ([[Discovery Records|Discovery]], 1950) with \"Strike Up the Band\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/Discovery.htm|title=DISCOVERY 78rpm numerical listing discography|website=78discography.com}}</ref>\n* [[Three Sounds]]  with \"One for Renee\" (Blue Note)<ref name=BlueNote/>\n* [[Steve Turre]] with [[James Carter (musician)|James Carter]] and [[Mulgrew Miller]] \u2013 ''TNT'' (2000)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Sarah Vaughan]] \u2013 1949<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Vic West]] ([[Planet Records|Planet]], 1957) with \"This Love of Mine\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/p/planet-oz.html|title=45 Discography for Planet Records - OZ |first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref>\n* [[Sheena Easton]] for her 1993 album ''[[No Strings (album)|No Strings]]'' and the OST for ''[[Indecent Proposal]]''\n* [[Kandace Springs]] on her 2020 album ''The Women Who Raised Me''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of 1930s jazz standards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Glenn Miller|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nearness Of You, The}}\n[[Category:Songs with music by Hoagy Carmichael]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Ned Washington]]\n[[Category:1938 songs]]\n[[Category:Pop standards]]\n[[Category:Glenn Miller songs]]\n[[Category:Jo Stafford songs]]\n[[Category:Shirley Bassey songs]]\n[[Category:1930s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in F major]]\n[[Category:Bluebird Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 1938 song|other articles with the same title|The Nearness of You (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Nearness of You\n| cover      = The Nearness of You Glenn Miller 78.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Glenn Miller]]\n| album      =\n| A-side     = The Nearness of You\n| B-side     = Mister Meadowlark\n| released   = {{Start date|1940}}\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1940\n| published  = 1940 by [[Famous Music]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Bluebird Records|Bluebird]]\n| writer     = [[Hoagy Carmichael]], [[Ned Washington]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''The Nearness of You'''\" is a [[popular music|popular song]] written in 1938 by [[Hoagy Carmichael]] with lyrics by [[Ned Washington]]. The song debuted in a 1940 recording by [[Glenn Miller]] and His Orchestra, with vocals by [[Ray Eberle]].<ref name=\"Maycock\">{{cite web|last1=Maycock|first1=Ben|title=Jazz Standards Songs and Instrumentals (The Nearness of You) |url=http://jazzstandards.com/compositions-0/thenearnessofyou.htm|website=jazzstandards.com|accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Covers==\nThe first big-selling version was recorded on April 28, 1940, by the [[Glenn Miller Orchestra]], with a vocal by [[Ray Eberle]] ([[Bluebird Records|Bluebird]]).<ref name=Gardner>{{cite book |title= Popular Songs of the 20th Century: Chart Detail & Encyclopedia, 1900-1949|last = Gardner|first = Edward Foote|publisher= Paragon House|location= St. Paul, Minnesota |year= 2000|isbn= 1-55778-789-1}}</ref><ref name=Blue10500>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/BB10500.htm |title=Bluebird Records in the 10500 to 10999 series|website=78discography.com}}</ref> This recording first reached the [[Billboard magazine|''Billboard'']] Best Seller chart on July 20, 1940, and lasted eight weeks on the chart, peaking at No. 5.<ref name=Whitburn>{{cite book| last = Whitburn| first = Joel| authorlink = Joel Whitburn| title = Top Pop Records 1940-1955 | publisher = Record Research| location = Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin| year = 1973 }}</ref>\n\nOther popular versions around that time were recorded by [[Kay Kyser]]'s orchestra (vocal: [[Harry Babbitt]], [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] catalog number 35488),<ref name=Gardner/><ref name=Col35200>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/COL35200.htm |title=Columbia Records in the 35200 to 35499 series|website=78discography.com}}</ref> by [[Dinah Shore]] with [[Paul Weston]]'s orchestra (Bluebird),<ref name=Gardner/><ref name=Blue10500/> and by [[Eddy Howard]] with [[Lou Adrian]]'s orchestra (Columbia).<ref name=Gardner/><ref name=Col35500>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/COL35500.htm |title=Columbia Records in the 35500 to 35999 series |website=78discography.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, [[Bob Manning (pop singer)|Bob Manning]] reached No. 16 on the pop charts with this song<ref name=pm>{{cite book |title=Pop Memories 1890\u20131954 |author=Whitburn, Joel |date=1986 |publisher=Record Research |page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/293 293] |isbn=0-89820-083-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/293 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|authors=Abrams, Steven & Settlemier, Tyrone |url=http://www.78discography.com/Capitol2000.htm |title=Capitol 2000 - 2500, numerical listing discography|website= Online Discographical Project|date= November 1, 2011|accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe 1956 [[Ella Fitzgerald]] and [[Louis Armstrong]] album of duets, ''[[Ella & Louis]]'', included a version of this song with Fitzgerald soloing vocally while Armstrong soloed both vocally and on trumpet. Accompaniment was provided by the small combo of the [[Oscar Peterson Trio]] featuring [[Oscar Peterson|Peterson]] on piano, [[Ray Brown (musician)|Ray Brown]] on [[Double bass|bass]], and [[Herb Ellis]] on guitar, joined by [[Buddy Rich]] on drums. The album reached No. 1 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine jazz chart and the top 10 of its pop chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hQoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA24|title=Billboard|date=24 November 1956|publisher=Nielsen Business Media}}</ref>\n\nGerman musician [[:de:Marc Secara|Marc Secara]] recorded the song with the [[Berlin Jazz Orchestra]] for the album ''You're Everything'' (2008). This was arranged for big band by [[Steve Gray (musician)|Steve Gray]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://marcsecara.de/berlin-jazz-orchestra/album-youre-everything/ |title=You're Everything|format=CD|authors=Secara, Marc & Berlin Jazz Orchestra & Gray, Steve (arr.)}} Track #2.</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\n* [[Louis Armstrong]] with [[Ella Fitzgerald]] \u2013 ''Ella and Louis''<ref name=\"standards\">{{cite book |last1=Gioia |first1=Ted |title=The Jazz Standards: A Guide to the Repertoire |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York City |isbn=978-0-19-993739-4 |pages=292\u2013295}}</ref>\n[[Ella Fitzgerald]] on her 1989 [[Pablo Records]] release  '[[All That Jazz (Ella Fitzgerald album)|All that Jazz]]\"\n* [[Connee Boswell]] with \"[[Blueberry Hill (song)|Blueberry Hill]]\"  ([[Decca Records|Decca]])<ref name=Decca3000>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/Dec3000.htm|title=DECCA (USA) 78rpm numerical listing discography: 3000 - 3500|website=78discography.com}}</ref>\n*[[James Taylor]] on ''[[American Standard (James Taylor album)|American Standard]]'' (2020)\n* [[Michael Brecker]] and [[James Taylor]] with [[Herbie Hancock]] \u2013 ''Nearness of You'' (2000)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Hash Brown]] (Philips, 1963) with \"I Got My Job Through The New York Times\"<ref name=Philips/>\n* [[Chick Bullock]]  with \"Fools Rush In\" (recorded April 26, 1940, [[Vocalion Records|Vocalion]])<ref name=Vocal5500>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/VOC5500.htm|title=Vocalion 78rpm numerical listing discography 5500 - 5600|website=78discography.com}}</ref>\n* [[Larry Clinton]] ([[Victor Records|Victor]], 1940) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/vic26500.html|title=VICTOR numerical listing discography|website=78discography.com}}</ref>\n* [[Cy Coleman]] with \"You Call It Madness\" ([[MGM Records|MGM]]) <ref name=MGM30500>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/MGM30500.htm|title=MGM Records - 78rpm numerical listing discography: 30500 - end of series|website=78discography.com}}</ref>\n* [[Bing Crosby]] recorded in 1954<ref>{{cite web|title=A Bing Crosby Discography|url=http://www.bingmagazine.co.uk/bingmagazine/CBS.html |website=BING magazine|publisher=International Club Crosby|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref> for his [[The Bing Crosby Show (1954\u20131956)|radio show]]<ref>{{cite web|title=allmusic.com|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-bing-crosby-cbs-radio-recordings-1954-56-mw0001951404|website=allmusic.com|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[Sammy Davis Jr.]] with \"Mad Ball\" ([[Brunswick Records|Brunswick]], 1957) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/b/brunswick-uk-05000-series.html|title=Singles Discography for Brunswick Records - UK - 05000 series|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Doggett]] (1970 [[King Records (USA)|King]]) with \"Moon Dust\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/k/king-6000-series.html|title=45 Discography for King Records - 6000 series|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Doggett]] with \"Honey\" (King)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/King4000.htm|title=KING 78rpm numerical listing discography: 4000 - 4500|website=78discography.com}}</ref>\n* [[Lou Donaldson]] with \"[[Mack the Knife]]\" ([[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]])<ref name=BlueNote>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/b/blue_note.html|title=45 Discography for Blue Note Records|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref>\n* [[The Flamingos]] (1965 [[Philips Records|Philips]]) with \"Don't Cheat On Me\"<ref name=Philips>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/p/philips.html|title=45 discography for Philips Records|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref>\n* [[Johnny Hartman]] - ''[[For Trane (Johnny Hartman album)|For Trane]]'' (Blue Note, 1995) (rec. 1972)<ref>{{cite book |last=Akkerman |first=Gregg |date=2012 |title=The Last Balladeer: The Johnny Hartman Story |series=Studies in Jazz, No. 68|location=Lanham, Maryland |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=9780810882812}}</ref>\n* [[Woody Herman]] with \"Johannesburg\" (recorded June 25, 1950, Capitol) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/Capitol1000.htm|title=Capitol 1000 - 1500, 78rpm numerical listing discography|website=78discography.com}}</ref>\n* [[Johnny Hodges]] \u2013 ''Wings and Things'' (1964)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Eddy Howard]] with \"Fools Fall in Love\" (Columbia)<ref name=Col35500/>\n*Etta James (album \u2018Time After Time\u2019)\n* [[Harry James]] (recorded May 1940, Varsity) with \"Mister Meadowlark\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/Vars8000.htm|title=Varsity 78rpm numerical listing discograp