oductions.info}}</ref>\n* [[Glenn Miller]] \u2013 1940<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Gerry Mulligan]] \u2013 ''Pleyel Jazz Concert Vol. 1'' (1954)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Willie Nelson]] on his [[American Classic]] album (2009)\n* [[Charlie Parker]] with the [[Woody Herman]] Orchestra \u2013 1951<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Joshua Redman]] and [[Brad Mehldau]] on [[Nearness_(album)|Nearness]] (2016)\n* [[Della Reese]] on ''An Evening with Della Reese'', 1958<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secondhandsongs.com/work/10851|title=Original versions of The Nearness of You written by Hoagy Carmichael, Ned Washington -  SecondHandSongs|website=www.secondhandsongs.com}}</ref>\n* [[The Roommates]] (1963, Philips) with \"Don't Cheat On Me\"<ref name=Philips/>\n* [[George Shearing]] and [[Nancy Wilson (jazz singer)|Nancy Wilson]] \u2013 ''The Swingin's Mutual'' (1960)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Dinah Shore]] (recorded June 25, 1940, Bluebird) with \"Maybe\"<ref name=Blue10500/>\n* [[Tab Smith]] ([[Checker Records|Checker]])<ref name=Checker-1>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/Checker.htm|title=Checker Records 78rpm numerical listing discography|website=78discography.com}}</ref><ref name=Checker-2>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/c/checker.html|title=45 discography for Checker Records|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref> and [[Quality Records|Quality]]<ref name=Quality>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/q/quality-ca-k-series.html|title=Singles Discography for Quality Records - CA - K series|first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref> both with \"[[Because of You (1940 song)|Because of You]]\"<ref name=Checker-1/><ref name=Checker-2/><ref name=Quality/>\n* [[Reinhold Svensson]] ([[Discovery Records|Discovery]], 1950) with \"Strike Up the Band\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://78discography.com/Discovery.htm|title=DISCOVERY 78rpm numerical listing discography|website=78discography.com}}</ref>\n* [[Three Sounds]]  with \"One for Renee\" (Blue Note)<ref name=BlueNote/>\n* [[Steve Turre]] with [[James Carter (musician)|James Carter]] and [[Mulgrew Miller]] \u2013 ''TNT'' (2000)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Sarah Vaughan]] \u2013 1949<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Vic West]] ([[Planet Records|Planet]], 1957) with \"This Love of Mine\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaldogproductions.info/p/planet-oz.html|title=45 Discography for Planet Records - OZ |first=Global Dog|last=Productions|website=www.globaldogproductions.info}}</ref>\n* [[Sheena Easton]] for her 1993 album ''[[No Strings (album)|No Strings]]'' and the OST for ''[[Indecent Proposal]]''\n* [[Kandace Springs]] on her 2020 album ''The Women Who Raised Me''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of 1930s jazz standards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Glenn Miller|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nearness Of You, The}}\n[[Category:Songs with music by Hoagy Carmichael]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Ned Washington]]\n[[Category:1938 songs]]\n[[Category:Pop standards]]\n[[Category:Glenn Miller songs]]\n[[Category:Jo Stafford songs]]\n[[Category:Shirley Bassey songs]]\n[[Category:1930s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in F major]]\n[[Category:Bluebird Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Arleyl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Italicize album titles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Nearness_of_You"}
{"title_page": "Jon Lebkowsky", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = Jon Lebkowsky\n| image        = Jonl.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| alt          =\n| caption      =\n| pseudonym    =\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1949|4|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   =\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| occupation   = Consultant, strategist, writer\n| nationality  = American\n| ethnicity    =\n| citizenship  =\n| education    =\n| alma_mater   =\n| period       =\n| genre        =\n| subject      = [[Social web]], [[world wide web|web]], [[cyberculture]], [[Internet]]\n| movement     =\n| notableworks =\n| spouse       = Marsha Lebkowsky\n| awards       =\n| signature    =\n| website      = {{URL|http://weblogsky.com}}\n| portaldisp   =\n}}\n\n'''Jon Lebkowsky''' (born April 20, 1949) is a web consultant/developer, author, and activist who was the co-founder of [[FringeWare, Inc.]] (along with [[Paco Nathan]]). FringeWare, an early attempt at [[ecommerce]] and [[online community]], published a popular \"[[magalog]]\" called [[FringeWare Review]], and a literary zine edited by Lebkowsky called [[Unshaved Truths]]. FringeWare's email list, called the FringeWare News Network, established an international following for the organization, which also opened a store in Austin, Texas.\n\nAlong with Nancy White, he co-hosts the ongoing Virtual Communities Conference, the Blog Conference, and the public Inkwell Conference at the seminal online community, the [[WELL (virtual community)|WELL]]. His weblog can be reached at [http://weblogsky.com Weblogsky.com]. He lives in [[Austin, Texas]].\n\n==Internet Advocacy==\nLebkowsky has a history of advocacy in support of a free and open Internet, and was a co-founder of [[EFF-Austin]], an organization formed to be a chapter of the national [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] (EFF). EFF-Austin became a separate organization with Lebkowsky as President. Lebkowsky coined the phrase \"Freedom to Connect,\" which became the name of an annual conference organized by [[David Isenberg]], as an alternative to the term \"network neutrality.\"\n\n==Early history==\nLebkowsky joined the WELL in 1990, and became a host or co-host of several forums on the conferencing system, including forums devoted to [[Factsheet Five]], where he had a brief stint as book review editor, and [[Mondo 2000]], where he wrote several articles and formed friendships with editors [[RU Sirius]] and [[Jude Milhon]]. Through the WELL, he also became associated with [[Howard Rheingold]] and [[Whole Earth Review]], the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]], and [[boing boing]], where he was Associate Editor. He had early associations with staff at [[Wired Magazine]] and conducted a regular, weekly series of chats called [[Electronic Frontiers Forum]] at [[HotWired]]. He was a subdomain editor for the [[Millennium Whole Earth Catalog]] and, in 1996, became a community host at Howard Rheingold's [[Electric Minds]].\n\nHe has been interviewed about his pioneering work for the documentary [[Traceroute (film)|Traceroute]].\n\n==Whole Foods Market==\nIn 1997, he joined [[Whole Foods Market]] as its \"Internet guy,\" to evangelize internally for the Internet and help lead their web-based ecommerce efforts, which ended in 2000 with the collapse of the so-called \"Internet bubble.\" As Internet evangelist within the company, he advocated creation of online community at [[WholeFoods.com]], and was Interactive Community Director for the ecommerce site that launched in 1998 The community included [[WELL Engaged]] forums and regular realtime chats using the IRC-based [[Talk City]] system. When WholeFoods.com was replaced by the ambitious [[Whole People]], Lebkowsky moved to Colorado and helped manage technology for the new enterprise until the company ended the project following the \"[[dot-com bubble|dotcom bust]].\"\n\n==Web Development, Social Software, and Blogs==\nLebkowsky turned to web development, and formed [[Polycot Consulting]] with [[Jeff Kramer]] and [[Matt Sanders]] on September 12, 2001. He became an advocate of Open Source systems based on PHP, and later Ruby on Rails.\n\nHe was an early influential [[social software]] advocate and one of the instigators of the [[Social Software Alliance]]. He was also an early blogger at [http://weblogsky.com Weblogsky]. With Clay Shirky, he created [https://web.archive.org/web/20110930150405/http://tagsonomy.com/ You're It], a blog about tags and [[folksonomy]]. He also blogged at, and managed technology for, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080518151456/http://www.worldchanging.com/ Worldchanging], an influential website focused on the future of sustainability that was inspired by the [[Viridian Design Movement]].\n\n==Bruce Sterling, Viridian Design, and the State of the World==\nHe is a close friend of author [[Bruce Sterling]], whom he has interviewed many times, and he created and operated the web site for Sterling's [[Viridian Design Movement]]. Lebkowsky and Sterling have a world-readable \"State of the World\" conversation for two weeks every January on [[The WELL]].\n\n==Writing==\nLebkowsky has written articles and essays, and is a contributing writer and columnist at [[Worldchanging]], and one of the contributors to the book [[Worldchanging: A Guide to the 21st Century]]. He was co-editor (with Mitch Ratcliffe) of the book ''[http://extremedemocracy.com/ExtremeDemocracy.pdf Extreme Democracy]''\n\n==Plutopia==\nIn the early 2000s, Lebkowsky was a member of the board of the Central Texas Digital Convergence Initiative (http://dcitexas.org/). In 2005, with other members of the Digital Convergence Initiative, he worked on an installation intended for the then newly established [[South_by_Southwest]] Interactive trade show, which was referred to in planning stages as Futurama. Due to a lack of time and funds, the installation did not occur as planned, however from planning conversations, Lebkowsky had the idea for a think tank that produces ''events'' instead of white papers. With futurist Derek Woodgate and consultant David Demaris, he put this idea into practice, creating an installation called the DIY House of the Future for Maker Faire Austin in 2007. The installation was successful. \n\nIn a debriefing about the installation, a small group discussed the idea of doing more events focused on a future where everyone's home and experience could be self-configured. Lebkowsky tossed out the idea of \"pluralist utopias,\" which led to adoption of the portmanteau \"Plutopia.\"\n\nLebkowsky and Woodgate, partnering with Maggie Duval and Bon Davis, created an event company, Plutopia Productions. Plutopia produced four large events during SXSW Interactive in Austin, in 2008 at Scholz Garten, 2009 at Palmer Events Center, and 2010-2011 at the Mexican American Cultural Center.\n\nAligned with the 2011 event, Lebkowsky and producer Scoop Sweeney created a podcast called the Plutopia News Network.\n\nLebkowsky left Plutopia Productions, which later closed down. However in 2018 Lebkowsky and Sweeney revived the Plutopia News Network podcast. https://plutopia.io\n\n== Other Projects==\nHe also led Austin's [[Wireless Future]] project for the [[IC\u00b2 Institute]] in 2003\u20132004, and was a prominent figure within the Central Texas [[Digital Convergence Initiative]], [[Bootstrap Austin]], [[ATX Equation]], and other local economic development projects.\n\nHe has been an advisor to the [[SXSW Interactive]] (SXSWi) conference for many years. He curated SXSWi tracks on wireless in 2004, digital convergence in 2006, and journalism in 2011. He was a cofounder and an original board member of the [[Society for Participatory Medicine]], and currently manages the Society's social media presence. He formed an Austin-based social web consultancy, [[Social Web Strategies]], where he was principal from 2006 to 2009. He was also instigator and principal of [[Plutopia Productions]], a future-focused entertainment and production company. He has also been involved in Austin sustainability projects, including [[Austin EcoNetwork]], [[Austin Green Art]], [[Austin 350]], [[Solar Austin]], and the [[Center for Maximum Potential Building Systems]].\n\nIn 2009 he left Social Web Strategies and returned to web consulting and development. He currently writes and speaks about the Internet, media, digital culture, and social technology. He has a web development and consulting company called [[Polycot Associates]], a spinoff from [[Polycot Consulting]].\n\n==Writings==\n* [http://www.weblogsky.com/writings.html List of links to writings and interviews.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110521191620/http://worldchanging.com/search/?blog_id=1&keyword=&category=&author=10&month=&search.x=22&search.y=13&search=Go Posts at Worldchanging.com]\n* [http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/story?oid=oid:597178 \"In Your Facebook\"]\n* [http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/story?oid=oid:613622 \"The Serious Play in Saving the World\"]\n\n==References==\n*{{cite web |url= http://www.austinchronicle.com/issues/vol15/issue48/screens.lebkowsky.html |title=Cyberculture Evolution |first1=Jon |last1=Lebkowsky |first2=R.U. |last2=Sirius |authorlink2=R. U. Sirius |editor=Jen Scoville |work=austinchronicle.com |date=August 1996 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}\n*{{cite web |url= http://technoccult.net/archives/2010/05/27/participatory-medicine-with-jon-lebkowsky-technoccult-interview/ |title=Participatory medicine with Jon Lebkowsky |first=Klint |last=Finley |work=technoccult.net |date=27 May 2010 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}\n*{{cite web |url= http://www.briancombs.net/3350/ |title=Austin's Internet Pioneers - Jon Lebkowsky |first=Brian |last=Combs |work=briancombs.net |date=16 December 2009 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Jon Lebkowsky}}\n* [http://weblogsky.com Weblogsky Blog]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070226185834/http://www.polycot.com/team/jon/ Polycot Team Listing]\n* [http://effaustin.org EFF-Austin]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061205053124/http://wirelessfuture.org/ Wireless Future]\n* [http://dcitexas.org Digital Convergence Initiative]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070219091606/http://www.worldchanging.com/bios/jonl.html Worldchanging Bio]\n* [http://www.itconversations.com/shows/detail1076.html Political Networks (ITConversations)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060429210542/http://www.authorviews.com/authors/lebkowsky/video.php AuthorViews video interview about Extreme Democracy]\n* [http://www.austinchronicle.com/issues/vol15/issue48/screens.lebkowsky.html From Zines to Zen: RU Sirius interviews Jon Lebkowsky] 1996\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090929053838/http://www.alterati.com/blog/?p=2295 Podcast interview with Jon Lebkowsky] 2009\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lebkowsky, Jon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = Jon Lebkowsky\n| image        = Jonl.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| alt          =\n| caption      =\n| pseudonym    =\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1949|4|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   =\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| occupation   = Consultant, strategist, writer\n| nationality  = American\n| ethnicity    =\n| citizenship  =\n| education    =\n| alma_mater   =\n| period       =\n| genre        =\n| subject      = [[Social web]], [[world wide web|web]], [[cyberculture]], [[Internet]]\n| movement     =\n| notableworks =\n| spouse       = Marsha Lebkowsky\n| awards       =\n| signature    =\n| website      = {{URL|http://weblogsky.com}}\n| portaldisp   =\n}}\n\n'''Jon Lebkowsky''' (born April 20, 1949) is a web consultant/developer, author, and activist who was the co-founder of [[FringeWare, Inc.]] (along with [[Paco Nathan]]). FringeWare, an early attempt at [[ecommerce]] and [[online community]], published a popular \"[[magalog]]\" called [[FringeWare Review]], and a literary zine edited by Lebkowsky called [[Unshaved Truths]]. FringeWare's email list, called the FringeWare News Network, established an international following for the organization, which also opened a store in Austin, Texas.\n\nAlong with Nancy White, he co-hosts the ongoing Virtual Communities Conference, the Blog Conference, and the public Inkwell Conference at the seminal online community, the [[WELL (virtual community)|WELL]]. His weblog can be reached at [http://weblogsky.com Weblogsky.com]. He lives in [[Austin, Texas]].\n\n==Internet Advocacy==\nLebkowsky has a history of advocacy in support of a free and open Internet, and was a co-founder of [[EFF-Austin]], an organization formed to be a chapter of the national [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] (EFF). EFF-Austin became a separate organization with Lebkowsky as President. Lebkowsky coined the phrase \"Freedom to Connect,\" which became the name of an annual conference organized by [[David Isenberg]], as an alternative to the term \"network neutrality.\"\n\n==Early history==\nLebkowsky joined the WELL in 1990, and became a host or co-host of several forums on the conferencing system, including forums devoted to [[Factsheet Five]], where he had a brief stint as book review editor, and [[Mondo 2000]], where he wrote several articles and formed friendships with editors [[RU Sirius]] and [[Jude Milhon]]. Through the WELL, he also became associated with [[Howard Rheingold]] and [[Whole Earth Review]], the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]], and [[boing boing]], where he was Associate Editor. He had early associations with staff at [[Wired Magazine]] and conducted a regular, weekly series of chats called [[Electronic Frontiers Forum]] at [[HotWired]]. He was a subdomain editor for the [[Millennium Whole Earth Catalog]] and, in 1996, became a community host at Howard Rheingold's [[Electric Minds]].\n\nHe has been interviewed about his pioneering work for the documentary [[Traceroute (film)|Traceroute]].\n\n==Whole Foods Market==\nIn 1997, he joined [[Whole Foods Market]] as its \"Internet guy,\" to evangelize internally for the Internet and help lead their web-based ecommerce efforts, which ended in 2000 with the collapse of the so-called \"Internet bubble.\" As Internet evangelist within the company, he advocated creation of online community at [[WholeFoods.com]], and was Interactive Community Director for the ecommerce site that launched in 1998 The community included [[WELL Engaged]] forums and regular realtime chats using the IRC-based [[Talk City]] system. When WholeFoods.com was replaced by the ambitious [[Whole People]], Lebkowsky moved to Colorado and helped manage technology for the new enterprise until the company ended the project following the \"[[dot-com bubble|dotcom bust]].\"\n\n==Web Development, Social Software, and Blogs==\nLebkowsky turned to web development, and formed [[Polycot Consulting]] with [[Jeff Kramer]] and [[Matt Sanders]] on September 12, 2001. He became an advocate of Open Source systems based on PHP, and later Ruby on Rails.\n\nHe was an early influential [[social software]] advocate and one of the instigators of the [[Social Software Alliance]]. He was also an early blogger at [http://weblogsky.com Weblogsky]. With Clay Shirky, he created [https://web.archive.org/web/20110930150405/http://tagsonomy.com/ You're It], a blog about tags and [[folksonomy]]. He also blogged at, and managed technology for, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080518151456/http://www.worldchanging.com/ Worldchanging], an influential website focused on the future of sustainability that was inspired by the [[Viridian Design Movement]].\n\n==Bruce Sterling, Viridian Design, and the State of the World==\nHe is a close friend of author [[Bruce Sterling]], whom he has interviewed many times, and he created and operated the web site for Sterling's [[Viridian Design Movement]]. Lebkowsky and Sterling have a world-readable \"State of the World\" conversation for two weeks every January on [[The WELL]].\n\n==Writing==\nLebkowsky has written articles and essays, and is a contributing writer and columnist at [[Worldchanging]], and one of the contributors to the book [[Worldchanging: A Guide to the 21st Century]]. He was co-editor (with Mitch Ratcliffe) of the book ''[http://extremedemocracy.com/ExtremeDemocracy.pdf Extreme Democracy]''\n\n==Plutopia==\nIn the early 2000s, Lebkowsky was a member of the board of the Central Texas Digital Convergence Initiative (http://dcitexas.org/). In 2005, with other members of the Digital Convergence Initiative, he worked on an installation intended for the SXSW trade show, which was referred to in planning stages as Futurama. Due to a lack of time and funds, the installation did not occur as planned, however from planning conversations, Lebkowsky had the idea for a think tank that produces events instead of white papers. With futurist Derek Woodgate and consultant David Demaris, he put this idea into practice, creating an installation called the DIY House of the Future for Maker Faire Austin in 2007. The installation was successful. \n\nIn a debriefing about the installation, a small group discussed the idea of doing more events focused on a future where everyone's home and experience could be self-configured. Lebkowsky tossed out the idea of \"pluralist utopias,\" which led to adoption of the portmanteau \"Plutopia.\"\n\nLebkowsky and Woodgate, partnering with Maggie Duval and Bon Davis, created an event company, Plutopia Productions. Plutopia produced four large events during SXSW